# ORBISAVE SYSTEM DESIGN CHECKLIST
> Purpose: Ensure scalability, reliability, security, and production readiness for a large-scale collective finance coordination platform.

---

## 1. SYSTEM OVERVIEW

- [ ] What problem does the system solve?
- [ ] What are the core user roles? (e.g. Admin, Group Admin, Member)
- [ ] What are the core flows?
  - [ ] Group creation
  - [ ] Member onboarding
  - [ ] Contribution tracking
  - [ ] Rotation/payout scheduling
  - [ ] Loan pool management
- [ ] What is NOT handled by the system? (e.g. money custody handled by banks)

---

## 2. ARCHITECTURE DESIGN

- [ ] Monolith vs Microservices vs Modular Monolith decision documented
- [ ] Backend framework defined (e.g. Django)
- [ ] Frontend architecture defined (e.g. Next.js)
- [ ] API design style:
  - [ ] REST
  - [ ] GraphQL (if applicable)
- [ ] Clear separation of concerns:
  - [ ] Auth
  - [ ] Business logic
  - [ ] Data layer
- [ ] System diagram exists (high-level + detailed)

---

## 3. DATABASE DESIGN

- [ ] Database type selected (PostgreSQL recommended)
- [ ] Core entities defined:
  - [ ] Users
  - [ ] Groups
  - [ ] Memberships
  - [ ] Contributions
  - [ ] Payout cycles
  - [ ] Loan pools
  - [ ] Transactions (logs, NOT money movement)
- [ ] Relationships normalized properly
- [ ] Indexing strategy defined
- [ ] Read vs write optimization considered
- [ ] Data consistency model defined
- [ ] Migration strategy exists

---

## 4. SCALABILITY (CRITICAL)

### Traffic Handling
- [ ] What happens if 10k users log in simultaneously?
- [ ] What happens if 100k users perform actions concurrently?
- [ ] What happens if 500k users click at once?

### Backend
- [ ] Horizontal scaling supported (stateless services)
- [ ] Load balancer configured
- [ ] API rate limiting in place
- [ ] Background job queues used (e.g. Celery, Redis)

### Database
- [ ] Read replicas configured
- [ ] Connection pooling implemented
- [ ] Query optimization tested
- [ ] Slow query logging enabled

### Caching
- [ ] Redis/memory caching used for:
  - [ ] Sessions
  - [ ] Frequently accessed data
- [ ] Cache invalidation strategy defined

---

## 5. PERFORMANCE

- [ ] API response times under load tested
- [ ] Frontend optimized:
  - [ ] Code splitting
  - [ ] Lazy loading
- [ ] Pagination implemented for large datasets
- [ ] Debouncing/throttling used in UI
- [ ] N+1 query problems eliminated

---

## 6. SECURITY (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

### Authentication & Authorization
- [ ] Secure authentication (JWT / OAuth)
- [ ] Role-based access control (RBAC)
- [ ] Multi-tenant isolation (groups cannot access each other)

### Data Protection
- [ ] HTTPS enforced everywhere
- [ ] Sensitive data encrypted at rest
- [ ] Secrets stored securely (no hardcoding)

### API Security
- [ ] Rate limiting
- [ ] Input validation & sanitization
- [ ] Protection against:
  - [ ] SQL Injection
  - [ ] XSS
  - [ ] CSRF

### Audit & Monitoring
- [ ] All critical actions logged
- [ ] Admin actions traceable
- [ ] Suspicious activity detection

---

## 7. RELIABILITY & FAULT TOLERANCE

- [ ] What happens if:
  - [ ] Database goes down?
  - [ ] API server crashes?
  - [ ] External bank API fails?
- [ ] Retry mechanisms implemented
- [ ] Circuit breakers used for external services
- [ ] Graceful degradation strategy defined
- [ ] No single point of failure

---

## 8. DATA INTEGRITY

- [ ] Transactional consistency enforced (ACID where needed)
- [ ] Idempotency for critical operations (e.g. contributions)
- [ ] Duplicate request handling
- [ ] Conflict resolution strategy

---

## 9. EVENT & JOB PROCESSING

- [ ] Background workers implemented for:
  - [ ] Notifications
  - [ ] Reports
  - [ ] Scheduled payouts logic
- [ ] Queue system selected (Redis, RabbitMQ, etc.)
- [ ] Retry + dead-letter queue strategy defined

---

## 10. INTEGRATIONS (BANKS / EXTERNAL SYSTEMS)

- [ ] API contracts clearly defined
- [ ] Timeout handling implemented
- [ ] Fallback mechanisms exist
- [ ] Logging of all external interactions
- [ ] No dependency blocking core system operations

---

## 11. MULTI-TENANCY (VERY IMPORTANT)

- [ ] Groups are fully isolated logically
- [ ] Data access scoped per group
- [ ] No cross-group leakage possible
- [ ] Tenant-aware queries enforced everywhere

---

## 12. LOGGING & MONITORING

- [ ] Centralized logging system
- [ ] Error tracking (e.g. Sentry)
- [ ] Metrics tracking:
  - [ ] API latency
  - [ ] Error rates
  - [ ] Active users
- [ ] Alerts configured for:
  - [ ] Downtime
  - [ ] High error rates
  - [ ] Performance degradation

---

## 13. DEVOPS & DEPLOYMENT

- [ ] CI/CD pipeline configured
- [ ] Environment separation:
  - [ ] Dev
  - [ ] Staging
  - [ ] Production
- [ ] Dockerized services
- [ ] Infrastructure defined (VPS / Cloud)
- [ ] Rollback strategy exists

---

## 14. TESTING

- [ ] Unit tests
- [ ] Integration tests
- [ ] Load testing (simulate 100k+ users)
- [ ] Security testing
- [ ] Edge case testing:
  - [ ] Simultaneous contributions
  - [ ] Double payout attempts

---

## 15. UX & FAILURE SCENARIOS

- [ ] Clear error messages for users
- [ ] Retry options in UI
- [ ] Offline/slow network handling
- [ ] No silent failures

---

## 16. FUTURE SCALABILITY

- [ ] Can this system support:
  - [ ] 1M users?
  - [ ] 10M users?
- [ ] Can new features be added without breaking core logic?
- [ ] Modular architecture for:
  - [ ] Loans
  - [ ] Investments
  - [ ] Analytics

---

## 17. COST OPTIMIZATION

- [ ] Efficient database queries
- [ ] Controlled API usage
- [ ] Scalable infrastructure costs
- [ ] Avoid over-provisioning early

---

## 18. DOCUMENTATION

- [ ] API documentation complete
- [ ] System architecture documented
- [ ] Developer onboarding guide exists
- [ ] Decision logs recorded (why choices were made)

---

# FINAL CHECK

- [ ] Can the system survive 500k concurrent actions?
- [ ] Can it recover from failure without data loss?
- [ ] Is user data secure?
- [ ] Is the system observable and debuggable?
- [ ] Can a new engineer understand and extend it quickly?

---

> If ANY of the above is unclear → system is NOT production ready.